<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-722-650  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 722 650.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Byte  Oct 1989 v14 n10 p364(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Goodbye, Mr. Chips. (Stop bit) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wayner, Peter.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Security was not a major concern on computer networks in the 1970sand early 1980s, when computer viruses were virtually unknown andhackers abided by an ethical code of not destroying information.andO;Victims of computer break-ins usually settled out of court inexchange for learning about leaks in the system.andP;  Today's hackerattacks have become far more damaging as networks have grown, andusers are less patient with the perpetrators of computer crimes.andO;Robert Morris, charged with creating the virus that crippledARPANET in Nov 1988, is being prosecuted under a 1986 lawprohibiting unauthorized use of federal computer systems.andO;Computers are no longer considered a 'liberating' technology.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     SecurityWide Area NetworksComputer CrimeFuture of Computing.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>